	                        <div id="dsq-comment-message-2555029123" class="dsq-comment-message">
	                            <div id="dsq-comment-text-2555029123" class="dsq-comment-text">
	                                <p>Hey Shairyar!</p><p>Ah, yea - that's a cool use for Twig. Yes, save them to the database (it's just easier anyways - no need to worry about file permissions on your web server, etc). Then, create your *own* twig service (instead of the core Twig service) and use *it* to render the templates. Literally, in service.yml, you'll have a new entry called something like 'email_template_twig' and you'll set the class to Twig_Environment and configure as needed. For this service, I wouldn't even use caching - you'll be rendering these templates so rarely, it won't matter much. And if you do use caching, you can set it to a specific directory (away from the normal Twig cache) and then delete that entire directory when one of the templates is updated.</p><p>Good luck - sounds cool!</p>
	                            </div>
	                        </div>
	                    </div>
